## 2. Deep-link configuration — bundle ID / Team ID / SHA collection

The MLabs template ships placeholder manifests at:

- `public/.well-known/apple-app-site-association`
- `public/.well-known/assetlinks.json`

Both contain `{{...}}` placeholders. They must be substituted with real
values before the production web app is deployed, otherwise universal
links will fall back to in-browser.

### Apple — collecting the values

```bash
# Apple Team ID (10 chars, alphanumeric):
#   https://developer.apple.com/account → Membership → Team ID

# Bundle identifier:
#   from mobile/app.config.ts → ios.bundleIdentifier
```

Substitute into `public/.well-known/apple-app-site-association`:

```diff
-       "appID": "{{APPLE_TEAM_ID}}.{{IOS_BUNDLE_ID}}",
+       "appID": "ABCDE12345.com.client.appname",
```

### Android — collecting the SHA-256

For EAS-managed signing keys (default for new MLabs projects):

```bash
cd mobile
npx eas credentials -p android
# select: production → keystore → show
# Copy the "SHA-256 Fingerprint" value (32 hex bytes separated by colons).
```

For Play App Signing (recommended in production — Google rotates the upload
key but the App signing key stays stable):

```
Play Console → App → Setup → App integrity → App signing
  → "App signing key certificate" → SHA-256 certificate fingerprint
```

> **Use the App signing key SHA, NOT the upload key SHA.** The upload key
> changes if you ever rotate it; the App signing key is what Android verifies
> against in the wild.

Substitute into `public/.well-known/assetlinks.json`:

```diff
-     "package_name": "{{ANDROID_PACKAGE}}",
+     "package_name": "com.client.appname",
      "sha256_cert_fingerprints": [
-       "{{ANDROID_CERT_SHA256}}"
+       "A1:B2:C3:...:8F:90"
      ]
```

### Verify

After deploying the web app with the substituted manifests:

```bash
npm run verify:deeplinks -- https://{{PROD_HOST}}
```

Expect all checks green. Red items block universal-link UX in the wild.

